WEBVTT

00:01.600 --> 00:03.124
Previously on The Good Wife...
The transmitter is
to be worn around

00:03.170 --> 00:04.569
your ankle
at all times.

00:04.600 --> 00:06.591
You're confined to the
apartment 24 hours a day.

00:06.640 --> 00:08.767
It must not
cross this line.

00:08.800 --> 00:10.165
Your condition is your...

00:10.210 --> 00:12.132
There is no condition!

00:12.180 --> 00:13.670
I'll be damned
if I'm going to have

00:13.710 --> 00:16.645
people think that Jonas Stern
is losing his mind.

00:16.680 --> 00:17.772
You've done wrong.

00:17.810 --> 00:19.141
I know I have.

00:19.180 --> 00:20.147
Your marriage
is in trouble

00:20.180 --> 00:23.047
because you don't acknowledge
true repentance.

00:23.090 --> 00:24.341
Tell me what I have to do.

00:24.390 --> 00:26.483
I'm going to take a
third of your business,

00:26.520 --> 00:29.250
and then I'm coming
back for the rest.

00:33.200 --> 00:37.660
OPPOSING LAWYER:
"At 5:16 pm. on September 5,
the explosion hit.

00:37.700 --> 00:39.565
"It was felt
over four blocks away.

00:39.600 --> 00:41.830
"Federal investigators
determined it was a pipe bomb

00:43.310 --> 00:45.130
"and anhydrous
hydrazine nitrate,

00:45.170 --> 00:46.376
"which had been thrown
through the window

00:48.710 --> 00:49.904
"No culprits
were ever apprehended,

00:49.950 --> 00:53.272
"and the federal government
continues to investigate.

00:53.320 --> 00:54.673
"The explosion killed
the plaintiff

00:54.720 --> 00:56.813
"Mr. Jeffrey Sanborn, 42,

00:56.850 --> 00:59.080
managing editor
of the Cook County Vindicator."

00:59.120 --> 01:00.348
JULIU_S:
Exception.

01:00.390 --> 01:02.722
"Resulted in his death."

01:02.760 --> 01:05.854
Uh, noted and accepted.

01:05.890 --> 01:08.859
Replacing "killed."

01:08.900 --> 01:09.924
"Mr. Sanborn is married

01:09.970 --> 01:12.131
"and has two teenaged
dependents who will suffer

01:12.170 --> 01:14.263
"from loss of wages
and affection.

01:16.670 --> 01:19.468
and severally, agree to pay..."
Uh, Julius?

01:19.510 --> 01:24.174
"$250,000 from capped
business insurance

01:24.210 --> 01:27.577
and $100,000 from capped
renter's insurance."

01:27.620 --> 01:30.111
But only if we agree now.

01:30.150 --> 01:31.310
We agree.

01:31.350 --> 01:34.148
Mrs. Sanborn?

01:34.190 --> 01:36.454
Mrs. Sanborn?

01:37.490 --> 01:41.221
The man_
you're discussmg--

01:41.260 --> 01:42.124
my husband--

01:42.170 --> 01:44.195
he was working
on a novel.

01:44.230 --> 01:45.561
I just started
reading it.

01:45.600 --> 01:49.536
It's... beautiful.

01:50.570 --> 01:52.902
And you're telling me

01:52.940 --> 01:58.139
that he's worth
$350,000?

02:00.250 --> 02:05.142
Mrs. Sanborn, no money could
ever replace your husband,

02:05.190 --> 02:07.658
but the only way
we can talk here

02:07.690 --> 02:09.624
is about money.

02:09.660 --> 02:11.184
I'm sorry.

02:11.230 --> 02:14.927
I've been reading a lot
of books about grief,

02:14.960 --> 02:17.190
and they all suggest
waiting six months

02:17.230 --> 02:19.767
before you make
any big changes in your life.

02:19.800 --> 02:23.201
Well, Jeffrey died
exactly

02:23.240 --> 02:26.437
six months ago
this week, so...

02:26.480 --> 02:28.436
you're fired...

02:28.480 --> 02:30.903
and you are, too.

02:30.950 --> 02:35.273
Mrs. Sanborn, if you do this,
we have to start over,

02:35.320 --> 02:37.709
and you may not get a better
settlement from our client.

02:37.750 --> 02:38.910
I think I will.

02:38.950 --> 02:41.180
Why?

02:41.220 --> 02:42.255
Why do you think that?

02:42.290 --> 02:44.383
Because I just hired
a new lawyer.

02:44.430 --> 02:45.488
(elevator bell dings)

02:45.530 --> 02:47.828
Jeanette!
Oh!

02:47.860 --> 02:50.829
Oh, how I missed you, baby doll.

02:50.870 --> 02:52.792
Ah, good to see you.

02:52.840 --> 02:56.833
Hey, get out of this hellhole,
come work for a real law firm.

02:56.870 --> 02:57.939
I have arrived.

02:57.970 --> 03:00.973
Mr. Stern,
thank you for joining us.

03:01.010 --> 03:05.276
Mrs. Sanborn, it is an extreme
and unconditional pleasure.

03:07.650 --> 03:09.288
Hello, Julius.

03:09.320 --> 03:12.209
I see you haven't
taken down the "S" yet.

03:12.260 --> 03:13.682
We're looking for a new Stern.

03:13.720 --> 03:14.948
Coffee, two sugars.

03:14.990 --> 03:15.809
Thanks.

03:15.860 --> 03:17.487
How about you three?
Anybody want coffee?

03:17.530 --> 03:18.781
(chuckles)

03:18.830 --> 03:20.491
Ah, it'll just
be one coffee.

03:20.530 --> 03:23.226
How are you feeling, Mr. Stern?

03:24.270 --> 03:26.488
How am I feeling, huh?

03:26.540 --> 03:30.408
Well, I'm feeling
like amending a complaint.

03:30.440 --> 03:31.998
How does
that sound?
Jonas,

03:32.040 --> 03:34.736
the insurance has been
capped at $350,000.

03:34.780 --> 03:36.577
The newspaper can't
pay anymore.

03:36.610 --> 03:39.249
Llnless_it was
an Intentional act.

03:39.280 --> 03:40.542
Intentional act
opens you up

03:40.580 --> 03:42.389
to punitive damages.

03:42.420 --> 03:44.684
I love when she
talks like that.

03:44.720 --> 03:46.688
It sounds so good coming
from a young person.

03:46.720 --> 03:48.585
How is it
an intentional act?

03:50.430 --> 03:52.853
Your client published

03:52.900 --> 03:55.425
an editorial cartoon
which depicts

03:55.460 --> 03:57.291
the Prophet Muhammad
being humiliated.

03:57.330 --> 04:00.037
Being body scanned
at an airport metal detector.

04:00.070 --> 04:03.005
And while all the other white
passengers are waved through.

04:03.040 --> 04:05.565
It was intended to criticize
raCIal profiling.

04:05.610 --> 04:07.498
All the while,
your client knew

04:07.540 --> 04:09.007
that Islam prohibits

04:09.040 --> 04:11.474
any pictorial depiction
of the Prophet,

04:11.510 --> 04:13.910
and he cut _back
on security

04:13.950 --> 04:15.474
at the exact moment
he should have increased it.

04:15.520 --> 04:16.885
A cost-cutting measure.

04:16.920 --> 04:18.148
Read the settlement,
Jonas.

04:18.190 --> 04:20.681
You know what happened in
Denmark when the Morning Post

04:20.720 --> 04:23.052
published cartoons
just like this.

04:23.090 --> 04:24.455
Riots,

04:24.490 --> 04:25.559
death threats.

04:25.590 --> 04:27.854
This isn't
about Mrs. Sanborn, Jonas.

04:27.900 --> 04:29.322
This is about us.

04:29.370 --> 04:32.589
Of course it's about us.

04:32.640 --> 04:34.631
I'm going to
destroy your firm.

04:35.870 --> 04:37.428
And Mrs. Sanborn

04:37.470 --> 04:39.904
understands that,
don't you, dear?

04:39.940 --> 04:41.339
I do.

04:42.850 --> 04:44.545
How much are you suing for?

04:44.580 --> 04:46.673
Didn't I ask for coffee?

04:46.720 --> 04:47.846
How much in punitive?

04:48.880 --> 04:51.087
$25 million.

04:51.120 --> 04:53.657
Here's the
amended suit.

04:53.690 --> 04:55.681
Mrs. Florrick.

04:56.590 --> 04:58.729
May I have a moment?

05:01.830 --> 05:03.422
How am I feeling?

05:03.470 --> 05:06.530
_ It was _
an Innocent question.

05:06.570 --> 05:08.538
Attorney-client privilege.

05:08.570 --> 05:12.734
What you know about me, what
you know about my condition

05:12.780 --> 05:15.431
is for us to know
and no one else.

05:15.480 --> 05:16.674
You do understand that?

05:18.410 --> 05:21.049
Oh, there it is again.

05:21.080 --> 05:22.047
(chuckles)

05:22.080 --> 05:23.240
That poker face.

05:23.290 --> 05:26.384
You know, I always thought
the CIA could learn something

05:26.420 --> 05:27.717
from the suburban
housewife.

05:27.760 --> 05:29.079
Do you understand?

05:29.120 --> 05:30.087
I understand

05:30.130 --> 05:32.121
the obligations of my job.

05:32.160 --> 05:34.458
Good.

05:37.100 --> 05:39.432
Oh, has your friend Will Gardner

05:39.470 --> 05:40.664
stabbed you in
the back yet?

05:40.700 --> 05:41.928
Would you like me
to get him

05:41.970 --> 05:43.506
on the phone for you?
You can ask.

05:43.540 --> 05:46.373
Ask him who he's
meeting with right now.

05:46.410 --> 05:48.469
Or does the name
Gerald Kozko

05:48.510 --> 05:50.649
mean anything
to you?

05:50.680 --> 05:51.977
He's a real estate developer.

05:52.010 --> 05:53.409
Underwater,

05:53.450 --> 05:56.749
and unless I'm mistaken,
his name keeps coming up

05:56.790 --> 05:58.781
_ in connection
With your husband's case.

06:01.160 --> 06:04.482
Always a pleasure,
Mrs. Florrick.

06:10.800 --> 06:13.530
(men laughing)

06:15.470 --> 06:17.665
Well, it's never
about the money.

06:17.710 --> 06:19.735
It's always about
something else.

06:19.780 --> 06:21.133
Well, I'm sorry
we can't help.

06:21.180 --> 06:23.375
Take care.

06:24.810 --> 06:26.778
Mrs. Florrick.

06:26.820 --> 06:28.617
Mister. . .?

06:28.650 --> 06:29.617
Kozko, Gerald.

06:29.650 --> 06:32.448
We've never met.

06:32.490 --> 06:33.957
How's Peter?

06:33.990 --> 06:35.116
Fine.

06:35.160 --> 06:36.149
I didn't know
you knew Will.

06:36.190 --> 06:37.122
I don't; I
was shopping

06:37.160 --> 06:40.027
for more lavwers to
join my defense team,

06:40.060 --> 06:42.767
but it appears we have
a conflict of interest--

06:42.800 --> 06:44.199
you.

06:44.230 --> 06:47.063
Aanay, glad
to meet you.

06:47.100 --> 06:49.193
Peter always said
he was a lucky guy.

06:49.240 --> 06:51.936
Now I see why.

06:52.980 --> 06:55.631
Would you tell Peter
something for me?

06:55.680 --> 06:57.841
Tell him I'm sorry.

06:57.880 --> 06:59.814
For?

06:59.850 --> 07:02.512
He'll know what I mean.

07:08.560 --> 07:11.779
Captioning sponsored by
CBS TELEVISION

07:22.540 --> 07:23.564
MAN: My great-grandfather
Lucius Clay

07:23.610 --> 07:25.737
founded the Vindicator.

07:25.770 --> 07:27.829
In his ﬁrst editorial
he endorsed Abraham Lincoln.

07:27.880 --> 07:31.179
In his last he railed
against Prohibition.

07:31.210 --> 07:32.575
The Trib and the Sun-Times

07:32.620 --> 07:34.144
may be bigger,

07:34.180 --> 07:36.045
but they have to answer
to corporate ownership.

07:36.080 --> 07:38.048
Dumbwaiters.

07:38.090 --> 07:40.012
Lucius set them up

07:40.060 --> 07:41.584
to shuttle in the booze.

07:41.620 --> 07:43.224
And so we gladly admit that

07:43.260 --> 07:44.750
we have committed this attack

07:44.790 --> 07:45.757
upon the blasphemous,

07:45.790 --> 07:46.927
who published this cartoon,

07:46.960 --> 07:47.949
to defend the honor

07:48.000 --> 07:48.955
of all Muslims

07:49.000 --> 07:50.262
and of Allah's beloved prophet.

07:50.300 --> 07:51.790
Peace be upon him.

07:51.830 --> 07:53.229
Yes, I've seen this.

07:53.270 --> 07:54.635
How does it hurt us?

07:54.670 --> 07:55.864
The plaintiff says
it's no secret

07:55.900 --> 07:57.538
this group's been active
in Chicago.

07:57.570 --> 07:58.662
Six months earlier,
they committed

07:58.710 --> 08:00.905
an identical bombing
at a synagogue.

08:00.940 --> 08:03.545
And you had to know that
cartoon might provoke them.

08:03.580 --> 08:05.047
My job is to provoke.

08:05.080 --> 08:06.069
Because it
sells papers?

08:06.110 --> 08:07.077
Because freedom
of the press

08:07.120 --> 08:10.544
is meaningless unless
somebody actually uses it.

08:12.590 --> 08:15.218
I'm not trying
to be insensitive.

08:15.260 --> 08:17.023
Jeff Sanborn was
a very good friend.

08:17.060 --> 08:18.550
We came up
together.

08:18.590 --> 08:20.228
The problem, Mr. Clay,
is their argument is,

08:20.260 --> 08:21.921
you did it
to increase circulation.

08:21.960 --> 08:24.269
It's not like I commissioned
this cartoon,

08:24.300 --> 08:26.268
hoping it was going
to anger Muslims.

08:26.300 --> 08:29.758
We had an online contest-: best
political cartoon, any subject.

08:29.810 --> 08:31.539
And you picked
the cartoon?

08:31.570 --> 08:33.629
In consultation with my editors.

08:33.680 --> 08:36.137
Jeffrey Sanborn, too?

08:36.180 --> 08:37.306
Sure,

08:37.350 --> 08:38.874
of course.

08:38.910 --> 08:41.014
JULIUS:
So, even if Stern can show

08:41.050 --> 08:42.608
he intended
this to happen,

08:42.650 --> 08:44.208
Sanborn was_
contributorlly negligent.

08:44.250 --> 08:45.217
Might not be a total win,

08:45.250 --> 08:47.013
but it's enough to get us
back to the table.

08:47.060 --> 08:48.982
We'll need something more
than Mr. Clay's testimony

08:49.020 --> 08:49.987
to establish it.

08:50.030 --> 08:51.554
What about
the cartoonist?

08:51.590 --> 08:52.750
It was an anonymous
submission.

08:52.800 --> 08:54.597
I sent the money
to a Paypal account.

08:54.630 --> 08:55.756
Routed through a proxy.

08:55.800 --> 08:56.994
There's no way
to trace it.

08:57.030 --> 08:58.964
We'll see.
I'll get Kalinda on it.

08:59.000 --> 09:01.036
*

09:01.070 --> 09:03.061
(laughter and chatter)

09:05.070 --> 09:07.072
(giggling)

09:09.710 --> 09:11.849
Returning to the
scene of the crime?

09:11.880 --> 09:13.711
You're not going
to pout, are you?

09:13.750 --> 09:16.878
I hate when men pout.

09:16.920 --> 09:19.138
Go away.

09:22.190 --> 09:24.750
Okay, let's inspect the
level of coincidence here.

09:24.790 --> 09:26.621
I haven't seen you
since college.

09:26.660 --> 09:27.888
We bump into
each other here.

09:27.930 --> 09:28.749
You ask me what I'm doing.

09:28.800 --> 09:30.825
I talk about the
Muhammad cartoon case,

09:30.870 --> 09:32.167
and then the next
day-- lo and behold--

09:32.200 --> 09:34.168
you and your firm
are suing my client.

09:34.200 --> 09:36.339
Cary, think about it.

09:36.370 --> 09:38.804
IfI let slip a piece
of information like that to you,

09:38.840 --> 09:42.173
you'd be on the phone to your
boss before our second drink.

09:42.210 --> 09:44.644
Okay.

09:48.120 --> 09:49.075
Then your turn.

09:49.120 --> 09:50.109
What's going
on at work?

09:50.150 --> 09:51.378
(laughs)

09:51.420 --> 09:54.753
Okay, I'll play.

09:54.790 --> 09:55.814
Stern wants you.

09:55.860 --> 09:57.725
Stern wants me?

09:57.760 --> 09:59.387
Last night you wanted
me, now he wants me.

09:59.430 --> 10:01.398
Lockhart, Gardner
is going under.

10:01.430 --> 10:03.796
It's a hollowed-out shell.

10:03.830 --> 10:05.661
Because Stern keeps
taking our clients.

10:05.700 --> 10:06.792
In one year,
your firm

10:06.840 --> 10:10.332
will be nothing but an empty
floor in an office building.

10:10.370 --> 10:13.305
Stern's got equity,
plenty of business,

10:13.340 --> 10:18.175
and one more thing:
no contest.

10:19.720 --> 10:24.214
That's right, your little
contest with Mrs. Florrick.

10:24.250 --> 10:25.740
You're losing.

10:25.790 --> 10:27.018
I got more billable hours.

10:27.060 --> 10:29.415
And Florrick's got
a name.

10:29.460 --> 10:31.018
Stern is new.

10:31.060 --> 10:33.824
There's a better path
to partnership.

10:33.860 --> 10:36.727
Think about it.

10:36.770 --> 10:37.862
You won't be alone.

10:37.900 --> 10:40.039
Oh, I won't be alone?

10:40.070 --> 10:42.061
In leaving
Lockhart, Gardner.

10:42.100 --> 10:43.328
You're raiding us?

10:43.370 --> 10:44.701
Mm-hmm.

10:46.710 --> 10:49.235
PETER:
So where are we
on getting me to church?

10:49.280 --> 10:50.406
I'm filing a
religious exception

10:50.450 --> 10:51.508
to electronic
monitoring.

10:51.550 --> 10:54.849
It doesn't always work,
but we'll hope for the best.

10:54.880 --> 10:56.211
Maybe next Sunday.

10:56.250 --> 10:57.740
ELI:
And I am getting a photographer
at the church.

10:57.790 --> 10:59.849
I don't care
what the good pastor has to say.

10:59.890 --> 11:01.915
Eli, we're not doing that.

11:04.090 --> 11:05.125
What is it?

11:05.160 --> 11:06.457
What's the mater?
Well, it's...

11:06.490 --> 11:08.048
probably nothing.

11:08.100 --> 11:11.399
Um, Childs is changing the
direction with the retrial.

11:11.430 --> 11:13.432
He's giving up
the sex angle.
What?

11:13.470 --> 11:14.789
That's all he's got.

11:14.840 --> 11:16.899
Is he changing
the trial date?
No.

11:16.940 --> 11:19.261
Two months away.
I don't understand, then.

11:19.310 --> 11:22.700
I am hearing chatter
about a surprise witness.

11:22.750 --> 11:25.048
E|i (sighs):
So who can hurt you?

11:25.080 --> 11:26.911
PETER:
Well, if they're
going to lie,

11:26.950 --> 11:28.838
anybody can hurt me.

11:28.880 --> 11:32.145
Maybe Childs is trying
to quietly make
this disappear.

11:32.190 --> 11:33.179
I doubt it.

11:33.220 --> 11:35.211
Hey, hon.

11:36.390 --> 11:39.086
Gerald Kozko was
at my office today.

11:41.330 --> 11:44.299
He wanted me to tell you
something.

11:44.330 --> 11:46.890
He said, "Tell Peter I'm sorry."

11:47.940 --> 11:49.999
Damn.

11:50.040 --> 11:52.133
No. Kozko and Childs
hate each other.

11:52.170 --> 11:54.138
There's no way he's going
to grant him immunity.

11:54.180 --> 11:56.432
Well, he would if it's
the only way to get Peter.

11:56.480 --> 11:57.799
We need...

12:00.180 --> 12:03.479
You're standing in my kitchen.

12:03.520 --> 12:05.784
Whatever you have to say,
you can say it in front of me.

12:08.820 --> 12:10.822
You heard her.

12:26.570 --> 12:28.777
Mrs. Sanborn,

12:28.810 --> 12:32.814
did your husband have a close
relationship with his employer?

12:32.850 --> 12:34.818
KAREN: Mr. Clay?

12:34.850 --> 12:36.818
Yes. Until recently.

12:36.850 --> 12:39.546
It had become strained--
their friendship.

12:39.590 --> 12:40.909
And why was that?

12:40.960 --> 12:42.450
Objection.
Beyond the scope.

12:42.490 --> 12:45.880
Well, I really think
we're safe here.

12:45.930 --> 12:47.898
Don't you?

12:47.930 --> 12:49.158
You may answer, Mrs. Sanborn.

12:49.200 --> 12:51.919
The paper was
in financial trouble.

12:51.970 --> 12:53.961
They had to lay off
a lot of staff.

12:54.000 --> 12:55.888
The stress took its toll.

12:55.940 --> 12:58.534
Jeff was also frustrated
by Mr. Clay's pursuit

12:58.570 --> 13:00.208
of a New Yorker cover.

13:00.240 --> 13:02.174
Something controversial.

13:02.210 --> 13:05.179
Like the Obama fist-bump cartoon
on the New Yorker.

13:05.210 --> 13:07.212
Something that would
increase readership.

13:07.250 --> 13:09.980
STERN: Well, Mrs. Sanborn,
did your husband help

13:10.020 --> 13:13.217
Mr. Clay choose the cartoon
for publication in the paper?

13:13.260 --> 13:14.284
KAREN: Yes.

13:14.320 --> 13:16.880
It was a contest, and he helped
Mr. Clay judge it.

13:16.930 --> 13:18.989
But the cartoon that appeared
was different,

13:19.030 --> 13:20.019
wasn't it?
Yes.

13:20.060 --> 13:21.197
I saw the original.

13:21.230 --> 13:23.198
It didn't depict Muhammad.

13:23.230 --> 13:25.061
It was just
a Middle-Eastern man.

13:25.100 --> 13:26.931
Jeffrey told me

13:26.970 --> 13:30.565
that the decision to change it
to Muhammad was Mr. Clay's.

13:31.910 --> 13:34.538
To generate more controversy.

13:34.580 --> 13:35.933
Is it just me,

13:35.980 --> 13:39.199
or do we really need
to find that cartoonist?

13:39.250 --> 13:41.047
So, here's your cartoon.

13:41.080 --> 13:42.843
Now, you see this
cross-hatching?

13:42.890 --> 13:44.084
How it almost
looks like bars?

13:44.120 --> 13:46.486
That can indicate a
